{
  "unmapped_findings": [
    "The fracture morphology of H90 steel shows common features of quasi-cleavage fracture with flat 'class cleavage' facets, micropores, tear edges, secondary cracks and dimples.",
    "The work hardening behavior exhibits three-stage characteristics: stage 1 (rapid decrease associated with ferrite deformation), stage 2 (slight decrease linked to TRIP effect, where WH rate increased with strain in range 0.03-0.15), and stage 3 (rapid decrease associated with deformation localization).",
    "Two types of retained austenite were identified: blocky austenite positioned at ferrite triple edges with high Schmid factors (0.45-0.48), and lath-like austenite located between ferrite laths or embedded in single ferrite grains with lower Schmid factors.",
    "Retained austenite with relatively small Schmid factors (<0.34) tends to remain untransformed during tensile deformation, while those with high Schmid factors transform first.",
    "The volume fraction of small angle grain boundaries increased with strain: 26% at ε=0.03, 31% at ε=0.10, 45% at ε=0.20, and over 51% at ε=0.27.",
    "Discrepancy noted: UTS of H90 reported as 846.4 MPa in Results section but as 836.4 MPa in Conclusions section.",
    "Martensitic transformation ratios after deformation: 63.1% for H70, 71.9% for H80, and 89.9% for H90.",
    "The M_s and M_d30 temperatures vary with solution temperature: H70 (33°C, 168°C), H80 (67°C, 204°C), H90 (120°C, 249°C)."
  ],
